                    <section class="portfolio tvEntry tvEntryOdd">
                        <div class="container">
                            <div class="row">
                                <div class="col-sm-12 portfolio-item">
                                    <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0475784/" class="portfolio-link" target="_blank">
                                        <div class="caption">
                                            <div class="caption-content">
                                                <i class="fa fa-search-plus fa-3x"></i>
                                            </div>
                                        </div>
                                        <img src="http://<?php echo $_SERVER['SERVER_NAME']; ?>/images/Blog/Best-of-Television/2016/The List/westworld.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="">
                                    </a>
                                </div>                    
                                <div class="col-lg-12 text-center">
                                    <div class="intro-text">
                                        <h2>1. Westworld</h2>
                                        <hr class="star-light">
                                        <span class="skills">HBO</span>
                                        
                                        <p class="centerText"><i>"Some people choose to see the ugliness in this world, the disarray. I choose to see the beauty. To believe there is an order to our days. A purpose."</i></p>
                                        
                                        <p class="centerText">What is consciousness?</p>
                                        
                                        <p class="mainText">Is it defined by a soul? Can it be manifested at will? Is it possible for a mechanical construct to make its own decisions? These are the central questions explored in the best new show of the year <i>Westworld</i>.</p>
                                        
                                        <p class="mainText">Created by former <i>Person of Interest</i> showrunner <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0634300/" target="_blank">Jonathan Nolan</a>, the show is based on a science fiction movie written and directed by <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000341/" target="_blank">Michael Crichton</a> also called <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0070909/" target="_blank">Westworld</a>. Although, because that movie was released in 1973, advances in technology have made it possible for this vision to be fully realized in a way that just wasn't feasible in the original film. In addition to this, because of the switch in format from film to television the robots, or <b>Hosts</b>, don't start their inevitable rebellion nearly as quickly. This gives the viewer the time necessary to sympathize with the Hosts before everything goes wrong. However, just as in the original film, this is not a normal robot uprising story.</p>
                                        
                                        <p class="mainText"><b>Westworld</b> is a theme park created by Dr. Robert Ford (played by <i>The Silence of the Lambs'</i> <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000164/" target="_blank">Anthony Hopkins</a>), an incredibly ambitious man who worked with his former partner Arnold to create an entire world set in a Western environment. Unlike somewhere like <b>Disney World</b> though, instead of rides the guests, also known as the <b>Newcomers</b> are offered experiences with the Hosts and are given the chance to make decisions that can help them discover who they really are. Yet, unlike the Newcomers, the Hosts have no such freedoms as is illustrated in this quote from the first episode:</p>
                                        
                                        <p class="centerText"><i>"What if I told you that there were no chance encounters. That you, and everyone you know, were built to gratify the desires of the people who visit your world? The people you call the newcomers. What if I told you that you can't hurt the newcomers, but they can do anything they want to you?"</i></p>
                                        
                                        <p class="mainText">This slavery, just as in most other robot uprisings, is what leads the Hosts to question who they are and what their purpose is. We're first introduced to this world through the eyes of Dolores (played perfectly by <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0939697/" target="_blank">Evan Rachel Wood</a>), our "girl next door" whom is destined to repeatedly have terrible things happen to her. Her supposed savior Teddy (played by <i>X-Men's</i> <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0005188/" target="_blank">James Marsden</a>) is powerless to save her against her tormentors, particularly the Man in Black (played ruthlessly by <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000438/" target="_blank">Ed Harris</a>), whose only concern is finding more information about <b>The Maze</b>.</p>
                                        
                                        <p class="mainText">Aside from Dolores, the other Host that is given the most focus over the course of the season is Maeve (played by <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0628601/" target="_blank">Thandie Newton</a>), whom has one of the most interesting arcs I've ever seen in any television show. The way Newton works her craft is incredible, effortlessly portraying the confusion, anger and sadness that her character experiences each week. Her storyline, which frequently has her interact with the men behind the curtains, is the most unique narrative of the bunch and always left me wanting more.</p>
                                        
                                        <p class="mainText">In addition to the Hosts, the rest of the human cast is excellent as well. One of the men behind the scenes, Bernard (played by <i>Hunger Games'</i> <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0942482/" target="_blank">Jeffrey Wright</a>) is a gifted engineer whom is investigating anomalies within the Hosts, such as the <b>Reveries</b> that Dr. Ford installs at the beginning of the series. Another key figure behind the veil is Theresa Cullen (played by <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0461746/" target="_blank">Sidse Babett Knudsen</a>, a senior manager whom's motives are hard to predict and is constantly at odds with Dr. Ford and his new narrative. Finally, there's William (played by <i>It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia</i> and <i>House of Cards'</i> <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0801051/" target="_blank">Jimmi Simpson</a>, a Newcomer whom crosses paths with Dolores and goes on a journey with her that will change his life forever. That journey will bring them closer together, but it will also lead Dolores to question her entire existence.</p>
                                        
                                        <p class="mainText">This self-reflection is part of the reason why <i>Westworld</i> has captivated the world with its mysteries this year. Not since <i>Lost</i> has there been a show that has driven so much community discussion about its mysteries. In a post-Reddit world, there are so many theorists out there now that many of the key mysteries were solved very early on which led to a lot of viewers discovering the end-game twists far earlier than anticipated. However, this is a show that can still be appreciated even with this foreknowledge and while I was made aware of some of the key plot movements beforehand, there were still plenty that took me by surprise before all was said and done.</p>
                                        
                                        <p class="mainText">That being said, this is a world that I looked forward to visiting more than any other each week, filled with a remarkable cast that continuously surprised me on a regular basis. While there won't be anymore of this show until 2018, this leaves the floor open for others to step it up and show what they can do.</p>
                                        
                                        <p class="centerText">Standout episodes for this year include <i>The Original</i>, <i>Tromp L'Oeil</i> and <i>The Bicameral Mind</i>.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </section>
                    
                    
